{
  "texts": [
    "The primary advantage of an absolute judge is its consistency and standardization in scoring across different responses.",
    "However, it may require extensive prompt engineering or fine-tuning to align with human scores (Kadavath et al., 2022).",
    "The relative judge, which we introduce next, mitigates it by making a direct comparison.",
    "However, it may introduce biases such as sensitivity to the order of the compared responses (Jeong et al., 2024).",
    "Absolute judge Relative judge Absolute judge Absolute judge Prompt x Response y Prompt x Response y1 Response y2 Prompt x Response y1 Response y2 LS / MN judge BTL judge BTL2 judge Text e Score b Text e Score b Text e1 Score b1 Text e2 Score b2 Absolute score Relative score Relative score Figure 1: Architectures of the least-squares (LS), multinomial (MN), Bradley-Terry-Luce (BTL), and two-headed BTL (BTL2) judges described in Section 4."
  ]
}